---
import BaseLayout from '@components/BaseLayout.astro';
import SectionHeading from '@components/SectionHeading.astro';
import InquiryBand from '@components/InquiryBand.astro';
import { product } from '@data/slabs';
---
<BaseLayout title="Natural Patagonia Granite" description="Learn about natural Patagonia Granite: Brazilian origin, mineral character, applications, thickness, finish, slab selection and project fabrication.">
  <section class="page-hero"><img src="/assets/images/hero/patagonia-granite-texture-close-up-01.webp" alt="Close view of large quartz and feldspar crystals in Patagonia Granite" /><div class="page-hero-content"><div><p class="eyebrow">Brazilian natural stone</p><h1>Patagonia, naturally composed.</h1><p>A pegmatitic granite built from oversized mineral crystals, deep contrast and occasional translucency—selected one slab at a time.</p><div class="button-row"><a class="button light" href="/slabs/">View slab selection</a><a class="text-link light-link" href="/contact/">Request a current lot →</a></div></div></div></section>
  <section class="section container split"><div class="split-copy"><p class="eyebrow">The material</p><h2>Scale you cannot reduce to a sample.</h2><p>Patagonia is a dramatic example of pegmatitic granite, a natural stone distinguished by unusually large mineral crystals. Individual slabs can move from ivory and champagne to rose, charcoal, silver or gold. The exact face—not the trade name alone—should drive the purchase.</p><p>Its quartz-rich areas may transmit light, while feldspar and dark mineral fragments create graphic contrast. For this reason, slabs should be photographed straight-on, examined close-up and, when relevant, tested with the intended backlighting system.</p></div><div class="split-media"><img src="/assets/images/hero/patagonia-granite-texture-close-up-04.webp" alt="Patagonia Granite mineral detail with black crystal and ivory field" /></div></section>
  <section class="section container"><SectionHeading eyebrow="Product specification" title="A project stone, clearly specified." /><div class="split"><div><table class="spec-table"><tbody><tr><th>Material</th><td>{product.material}</td></tr><tr><th>Origin & processing</th><td>{product.origin}</td></tr><tr><th>Thickness</th><td>{product.thicknesses.join(' · ')}</td></tr><tr><th>Finishes</th><td>{product.finishes.join(' · ')}</td></tr><tr><th>Availability</th><td>{product.availability}</td></tr><tr><th>Lead time</th><td>{product.leadTime}</td></tr></tbody></table><p class="notice">Natural stone varies by slab and lot. Confirm current photos, quantities, dimensions and finish before approving an order.</p></div><div><h3>Best suited for</h3><ul>{product.applications.map((item)=><li>{item}</li>)}</ul><h3>Selection notes</h3><ul><li>Approve the exact slab face and focal area.</li><li>Check slab-to-slab continuity for multi-piece work.</li><li>Plan joints, openings and waterfall returns before cutting.</li><li>Test translucent areas with the intended lighting setup.</li></ul></div></div></section>
  <section class="section container split reverse"><div class="split-media"><img src="/assets/images/applications/patagonia-granite-hotel-reception-counter-01.webp" alt="Patagonia Granite hotel reception counter and feature wall" loading="lazy" /></div><div class="split-copy"><p class="eyebrow">Design with the actual slab</p><h2>Let the mineral field set the composition.</h2><p>For large-format walls, islands and reception counters, the most valuable detail is often placement. A scaled dry layout lets designers choose what stays uninterrupted, where seams disappear and how the strongest crystal field turns a corner.</p><a class="text-link" href="/applications/">Explore applications →</a></div></section>
  <InquiryBand title="Select the exact Patagonia slab for your project" />
</BaseLayout>
